BOOYSENS SAPS responded to a complaint of a suspected truck hijacking. It is reported that the cargo truck which was traveling from Durban Harbour was followed by the suspects’ vehicles from N3 near Leondale to its destination in Aeroton warehouse. SAPS spokeswoman Colonel Brenda Muridili said: “At the warehouse, suspects removed the consignment from the truck and loaded it into the bakkie. The on-duty police officials cornered the suspects’ vehicle as they were about to flee the scene.” The incident happened on Friday, 9 July at the Aeroton business premises. Muridili said upon arrival, members found a black Nissan bakkie parked and searched it. “While searching they found 23 big bags containing cocaine with an estimated street value of R200 million,” she said.  Muridili said when the the driver of the bakkie was questioned, it was found that he is a police warrant officer attached to Zonkezizwe Police Station and that the bakkie belongs to the state. “He was immediately arrested on the scene together with his three accomplices – another police warrant officer attached to National Investigative Unit, a Gauteng chief traffic officer and a civilian,” she explained. Muridili said members further confiscated 552 bricks of cocaine, four vehicles, a grey BMW including three state vehicles (VW GTI, Kia Cerato and a Nissan bakkie) as well as R60 000 in cash. The suspects aged between 35 and 42 will appear in the Booysens Magistrates Court facing charges that include robbery, dealing in drugs and defeating the ends of justice on Monday, 12 July.